int cl_file_inode_init(struct inode *inode, struct lustre_md *md)
{
        struct lu_env        *env;
        struct ll_inode_info *lli;
        struct cl_object     *clob;
        struct lu_site       *site;
        struct lu_fid        *fid;
        struct cl_object_conf conf = {
                .coc_inode = inode,
                .u = {
                        .coc_layout = md->layout,
                }
        };


So.... this opens up a question - how come there's no crashing with access to invalid inodes? At least I don't remember seeing any.

 > Is ll_dirty_page_discard_warn() called with a lock on the page.
 > If it is, then it shouldn't be possible for the bug to happen.
 > If it is not, them it shouldn't be doing anything with
 > page->mapping->host.
 > 
 > As it only wants the inode for an error message, I would suggest
 > trylock_page().  If that succeeds, then get the inode, find a
 > dentry and use "%pD4" to print out the dentry.
 > If the trylock fails, or the inode is NULL, or the dentry cannot be
 > found, just print a generic message.

looks like we have a bigger mess to untangle anyway (or at least understand why it has not pcaused any problems so far)
